1.  How to design a scalable database?
    Sharding               Split data across multiple DB servers (e.g. users A-M on server 1, N-Z on server 2)
    Read replicas          Master handles writes, replicas handle reads — reduces load
    Caching                Use Redis/Memcached to serve frequent reads without hitting DB
    NoSQL when needed      For certain data types (sessions, logs), NoSQL scales better

2.  What is data replication?
    Replication = copying data from one DB server to one or more others automatically and continuously.
    Why?               High availability (if one server dies, others take over), load balancing, disaster recovery
    Master-Slave       One master handles writes, slaves sync and handle reads
    Master-Master      Multiple masters can accept writes — more complex but more resilient

3.  NoSQL database types and when to use them
    Document (MongoDB)      Store JSON-like docs. Good for user profiles, content
    Key-Value (Redis)       Super fast lookups. Good for caching, sessions
    Column (Cassandra)      Time-series, real-time analytics
    Graph (Neo4j)           Relationships-heavy data — social networks, recommendations

4.  What is ETL?
    ETL = Extract, Transform, Load — a pipeline to move data from multiple sources into a data warehouse.
    Extract       Pull data from sources (databases, APIs, files)
    Transform     Clean it, fix formats, remove duplicates, apply business rules
    Load          Push the clean data into the target warehouse

5.  Database security best practices
    Encrypt data at rest (AES)
    Encrypt in transit (TLS/SSL)
    Least privilege access
    Role-based access control
    Audit logs
    Data masking in dev/staging
    Regular backups
